Part 1: Data Cleaning¶

a. Missing Value Handling¶

There are missing values in "WorkClass" and "Occupation" columns, which probably indicate that these people have no occupation. We don't want to delete them because they can actually indicates an income bracket of lower than 5k. We can fill in these missing values with "None".

The missing values in the "Native Country" probably indicate that these people were born in a country other than United-States, Cambodia, England, Puerto-Rico, Canada, Germany, Outlying-US(Guam-USVI-etc), India, Japan, Greece, South, China, Cuba, Iran, Honduras, Philippines, Italy, Poland, Jamaica, Vietnam, Mexico, Portugal, Ireland, France, Dominican-Republic, Laos, Ecuador, Taiwan, Haiti, Columbia, Hungary, Guatemala, Nicaragua, Scotland, Thailand, Yugoslavia, El-Salvador, Trinadad&Tobago, Peru, Hong, Holand-Netherlands. We can fill in theses missing values with "Other".

#filling in missing values

b. Converting Categorical Data to Numerical¶

Now, as there are no missing values in the data, we can convert categorical data into numerical data.

The 'Education' column is not useful since we have 'Educationlvl' which represents education in continuous data.

We want to use labels encoding for income bracket because these are the target values of model prediction and the increase in label number can actually indicates increase in income. We will represents income lower than 50K as 0, 50-100K as 1, income higher than 100K as 2.

For all the other categorical data we will use one hot encoding. Models assumes that numerical features reflect algebraic quantities, but that is not the case for the categorical data we have here. For example, if we assign male as 0, female as 1, this would imply male < female which doesn't make sense. Thus, we want to use one hot encoding instead of label encoding for the rest of categorical data.

In [62]:
#drop Education column
income_training = income_training.drop('Education', axis=1) 
income_testing = income_testing.drop('Education', axis=1) 

#label encoding IncomeBracket

cleaned_income_testing = income_testing

Part 3: Feature Selection¶

Dummy variables were created additionally for one-hot labeling based on the original features of the dataset. This type of feature engineering is called feature representation. Feature engineering is a usefull tool in machine learning because it creates new features from existing ones and it is one of the most effective ways to improve model performance. Through feature engineering, we can isolate key information, highlight patterns and bring in domain expertise.

Based on the original features, we can also add a new feature called 'Invest' which indicates whether an individual do investments. This can be generated based on the 'CapitalGain' and 'CapitalLoss' features. If an individual has 'CapitalGain' or 'CapitalLoss' other than 0 then he/she has 'Invest' of 1, else he/she has 'Invest' of 0. This type of feature engineering is called indicator variables which involves using indicator variables to isolate key information.

Part 4: Model Implementation¶

We write run_kforld() that will be used for cross-validation, and plot_learning_curve() that will be used for plotting learning curves.

In [19]:
def run_kfold(classifier):
    
    #run KFold with 10 folds on the 891 records in the training_data
    kf = KFold(len(X.values), n_folds=10)
    
    #initiate the outcome and counter
    train_outcomes = []
    test_outcomes = []
    fold = 0
    
    #get the train and test index from the KFold records 
    for train_index, test_index in kf:
        fold += 1
        #get the training input and testing input from KFold records
        X_train, X_test = X.values[train_index], X.values[test_index]
        #get the training output and testing output from KFold records
        y_train, y_test = y.values[train_index].ravel(), y.values[test_index].ravel()
        
        
        #find out the cross relationship between the training input and output
        classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)
        #predict the training result using the model we just trained before
        train_predictions = classifier.predict(X_train)
        #predict the testing result using the model we jsut trained before
        test_predictions = classifier.predict(X_test)
        
        #compare the train set values and get the accuracy
        train_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_train, train_predictions)
        #compare the test set values and get the accuracy
        test_accuracy = accuracy_score(y_test, test_predictions)
        #put the training accuracy into the outcome
        train_outcomes.append(train_accuracy)
        #put the training accuracy in the outcome
        test_outcomes.append(test_accuracy)
        print("Fold {0} training and testing accuracy: {1}, {2}".format(fold, train_accuracy, test_accuracy))   
    
    #calculate the mean train value
    mean_train_outcome = np.mean(train_outcomes)
    #calculate the mean test value
    mean_test_outcome = np.mean(test_outcomes)
    print("Mean Training and Testing Accuracy: {0}, {1}".format(mean_train_outcome, mean_test_outcome)) 
    return mean_train_outcome, mean_test_outcome

def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None, n_jobs=1,\
                        train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5), scoring='accuracy'):
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
    plt.title(title)
    
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
        
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel(scoring)
    
    #get training score and test score from learning curve
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(estimator, X, y, cv=cv, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    
    plt.grid()

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,\
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1, \
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,\
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="g")
    
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g", label="Cross-validation score")
    plt.legend(loc="best")
    
    return plt

a. Decision Tree¶

Decision Tree is a classification algorithm that produces rules using attributes data that can be used to classify data.

Pros: Decision Tree is easy to understand and visualize, it can handle both numerical and categorical data. Cons: Decision tree can create complex trees that do not generalise well, and small variations in the data might result in a completely different tree being generated.

I choose this algorithm because it is efficient and easy to understand.

b. Random Forest¶

Random forest classifier fits a number of decision trees on various sub-samples of datasets and uses average to improve the model prediction accuracy and controls over-fitting.

Pros: Decrease in overfitting, usually more accurate than decision trees. Cons: Slow real time prediction, algorithm is complex and difficult to implement.

I choose random forest classifier because I want to see if it is more accurate than decision tree model in this problem.

c. K-Nearest Neighbours¶

K-Nearest Neighbours classification is computed from a simple majority vote of the k nearest neighbours of each point.

Pros: The algorithm is simple to implement, robust to noisy training data, and effective if training data is large. Cons: The number K has to be determined and the computation cost is high as it needs to computer the distance of each instance to all the training samples.

I choose this model because we have large training data and it is an effective algorithm when training data is large.

d. Gradient Boosting¶

Gradient Boosting uses residual function as graident of the learning model at iteration. It produces a prediction model in the form of an ensemble of weak prediction models, typically decision trees. It uses boosting which is an ensemble technique in which the predictors are not made independently, but sequentially.

Pros: It minimize residuals on training data, reduce bias and variance. Cons: Training process can require a lot of computation. Hard to interpret. Overfitting can occur.

I choose this algorithm because it can achieve excellent accuracy and reduce bias. I also want to see if gradient boosted trees actually perform better than a random forest.

In [34]:
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, classes,
                          normalize=False,
                          title='Confusion matrix',
                          cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    
    #normalize confusion matrix data
    cm = cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
    print("Normalized confusion matrix")

    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(classes))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, classes, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, classes)

    fmt = '.2f' if normalize else 'd'
    thresh = cm.max() / 2.
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        plt.text(j, i, format(cm[i, j], fmt),
                 horizontalalignment="center",
                 color="white" if cm[i, j] > thresh else "black")

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')

From the accuracy table we can see that, the testing accuracy of test set is 0.00797 lower than that of training set, which is not a significant difference. The TPR on income bracket 2 of the test set is lower than that of training set, but the TPR on income bracket 1 and 3 of test set is higher than that of the training set. We would say the accuracy on test set is slightly worse than that of the training set.

In term of bias-variance trade-off, the accuracy variance on test set is slightly larger than that on training set but both do not have overfitting since the difference between mean accuracy is smaller than 0.1, the distance between training score and validation score on the learning curve plots are also small when the amount of training samples gets high. The model encounters underfitting on both the training set and the test set because the validation score increases while the training score decreases on both learning curves.

As I said in part 5, to increase the accuracy and reduce underfitting of this model, we can tune it further with larger hyperparameter range and add more hyperparamters such as 'min_samples_leaf' and 'min_samples_split' so that grid search will have more alternatives to choose for best estimators. We could also try with more or less data features to see if it actually improves the prediction accuracy. Feed in too much features can confuse classifier if they don't have obvious correlation with IncomeBucket. Classifier may not have enough attributes if we feed in very little amount of features. The model accuracy can be affected in both cases. We could spend more time on selecting the best andfeatures
